The functional groups of FCE and FM-CQDs were characterized by ATR-FTIR analysis. The functional group of FCE exhibited a broad peak at 3857.9, 3743.15 and 3264.89 cm−1 indicates the presence of O–H carboxylic acids, which are similar to those in the FM-CQDs (Fig. 4
                        ). The presence of peak at 1500-600 cm⁻1 in the FCE attributable to various vibration of C–O, CC, C–N and C–Br, this vibration indicates the functional group of Alkyl aryl ether, Alkene, Benzene derivative and halo compound (Table 2
                        ). Functional groups may act as precursors in the synthesis of FM-CQDs. The FM-CQDs peaks at 3443.2, 3052.76 cm−1 indicated the presence of O–H alcohols group and two while mild peaks at 2937.06 and 2937.06 cm−1 are attributed to the existence of C–H alkanes groups, which are clearly associated with the synthesized carbon quantum dots (Fig. 5
                        ). Additionally, the strong signal at 1800 cm⁻1 suggested the presence of CO conjugated anhydrides, 1577.49 cm−1 aliphatic ketones, CC cyclic alkenes and 1394.28 cm−1 O–H alcohol. The aromatic esters and alkene groups obtained in FCE are essential functional groups that react together to form the carbon core material of the FM-CQDs (Table 3
                        ). Moreover, the analyses revealed that the presence of O–H and C–H vibrations indicates the presence of organic matter in the FCE and FM-CQDs and CC vibrations, suggesting the successful formation of FM-CQDs (Fig. 5).

HR-TEM revealed the morphology and particle-size distribution of the synthesized carbon quantum dots (CQDs). The FM-CQDs exhibited monodispersed characteristics with a narrow size distribution. The average particle size of ∼7.34 nm with 1.7 nm diameter distribution was obtained by HR-TEM analysis (Fig. 6
                        f). The particle size and distribution were calculated using 20 nm scanning scale image (Fig. 6a) using ImageJ software (NIH). The 2 nm and 5 nm scanned images of TEM revealed a uniform distribution of the FM-CQDs, showing their distinct size and clustered pattern (Fig. 6b and d). The electron diffraction pattern of the FM-CQDs consisted of C and O molecules. The ring pattern showed a diffuse halo, devoid of bright sharp rings, indicating the amorphous nature of the FM-CQDs (Fig. 6e). In addition to the FM-CQDs confirmation, X-ray diffraction (XRD) analysis was performed to determine the crystallinity of the FM-CQDs. The broad peak centered at 23.5° at 2θ corresponding to the carbon plane (002). The XRD pattern indicates a hard carbon material with an amorphous nature, which indicates a lack of well-defined crystalline structures (Fig. 7
                        ).

Plants treated with FCE or FM-CQDs exhibited significant differences in plant height, leaf number and leaf area in a concentration-dependent manner. The 80 mg L−1 concentration of FCE showed maximum height of the plant (21.0 ± 1.2 cm plant−1), number of leaves (3.5 ± 0.1 plant−1), and leaf area (175.0 ± 4.0 cm2 plants−1) (Table 4
                        ). The control and plants treated with 40, 60, and 100 mg L−1 FCE exhibited minimal plant growth (Fig. 8
                        a). Plants treated with different concentrations of the FM-CQDs played a major role in plant growth (Fig. 8b). The results exhibited an average height of 25.0 ± 1.4 cm plant−1, 3.5 ± 0.1 plant−1 number of leaves, and 146.0 ± 4.2 cm2 plant−1 a leaf area of per plant at 4 mg L−1. The high concentration at 5 mg L−1 of FM-CQDs retracted the plant growth parameters and showing 13.0 ± 0.6 cm plant−1 in height, 3.0 ± 0.1 plant−1 leaves, and 91.0 ± 2.1c cm2 plant−1 in leaf area. These results suggest that optimum concentrations of both extracts can promote plant growth.

The superoxide dismutase (SOD) activity of C. longa increased by 80.3% in plants treated with 80 mg L−1 of FCE. Whereas, plants treated with FM-CQDs at 4 mg L−1 concentration showed 77.04% of SOD activity whereas, control group exhibited 72.7% SOD activity (Fig. 12
                        ) while other concentration treated with FCE and FM-CQDs also shows the significant impact on SOD activity, there was no significant impact observed in FCE at 100 mg L−1 and FM-CQDs at 5 mg L−1 on SOD activity when compared with the control. The peroxidase (POD) activity also increased in response to both treatment groups. The highest activity of 33.25 μmol mg protein−1 was observed in plants treated with 80 mg L−1 of fungal extract and 21.50 μmol mg protein−1 was recorded by FM-CQDs at 4 mg L−1 (Fig. 13
                        ). Both treatments showed a dose dependent response with lower activities observed at higher concentrations of FCE (14.44–17.28 μmol mg protein−1) and FM-CQDs (12.53–19.3 μmol mg protein−1). Catalase (CAT) activity of control and treated groups were tested and found highest catalase activity (234.8 μmol mg protein−1) at 80 mg L−1 concentration of FCE (Fig. 14
                        ). Similarly, FM-CQDs at 3 mg L−1 concentration of treated plants showed maximum of catalase activity of 237.1 μmol mg protein−1 and control plant showed only 66.6 μmol mg protein−1 of catalase activity (Fig. 14).
